05:09.676 --> 05:12.712
[♪ ominous music ♪]

05:12.712 --> 05:16.712
♪♪♪

05:22.455 --> 05:25.325
[tires screech]

05:45.111 --> 05:46.479
Hey.

05:49.983 --> 05:51.418
We're late.

05:54.621 --> 05:57.424
I love being here with you.

05:57.424 --> 05:59.226
Let's just stay here forever,

05:59.226 --> 06:01.461
and I could write one book
after another, get rich,

06:01.461 --> 06:04.764
buy Robert and Yvonne's house
right out from under them.

06:04.764 --> 06:06.433
[laughs] And what will I be doing

06:06.433 --> 06:08.268
while you're busy writing?

06:08.268 --> 06:10.370
You'd be my muse.

06:13.673 --> 06:16.109
You know you can trust me, right?

06:16.109 --> 06:18.511
Yeah, of course.

06:20.380 --> 06:23.216
You know, you can... you can
tell me whatever you want.

06:23.216 --> 06:26.519
You don't have to hide anything.

06:28.121 --> 06:30.657
I don't. [laughs]

06:34.127 --> 06:37.664
Tell me a secret.
Something nobody else knows.

06:40.467 --> 06:43.236
I hate beets. [laughs]

06:43.236 --> 06:44.971
- [laughs]
- Come on, seriously.

06:44.971 --> 06:46.606
We can't be late.

06:46.606 --> 06:49.409
They're not the kind of
people that find that charming.

07:04.658 --> 07:06.426
[drawer rattles]

07:08.295 --> 07:10.397
[drawer rattles]

07:10.397 --> 07:13.099
What would you say if
I asked you to marry me?

07:13.099 --> 07:15.969
It would depend on the ring.

07:15.969 --> 07:17.671
[chuckles]

07:28.281 --> 07:30.317
Would that be okay?

07:30.317 --> 07:32.218
What's that?

07:34.054 --> 07:36.256
What's it look like?

07:36.256 --> 07:38.191
- You can't. Stop.
- Come here. Come here.

07:38.191 --> 07:41.261
Come here.

07:41.261 --> 07:45.198
I want you to know how much you mean to me.

07:45.198 --> 07:47.300
These last six weeks here have been

07:47.300 --> 07:51.504
the best of my whole life,
and I know it's crazy, but...

07:56.443 --> 07:57.978
What's wrong? You okay?

07:57.978 --> 07:59.612
Yeah, I'm just... [exhales sharply]

07:59.612 --> 08:02.248
...overwhelmed.

08:03.717 --> 08:05.285
It's okay. It's too soon.

08:05.285 --> 08:06.186
I'm an idiot. I shouldn't have...

08:06.186 --> 08:08.621
Yes.

08:08.621 --> 08:10.056
Yes what?

08:10.056 --> 08:11.524
Yes, I want to marry you.

08:13.360 --> 08:15.395
You sure?

08:15.395 --> 08:17.764
Put it on me.

08:17.764 --> 08:19.466
[chuckles]

08:23.336 --> 08:25.205
- [laughs]
- You sure?

08:25.205 --> 08:26.239
Yeah.

08:26.239 --> 08:30.343
[both laugh]

08:30.343 --> 08:32.544
[Yvonne] Oh, it's just so sweet.

08:32.544 --> 08:35.048
[Robert and Yvonne laugh]

08:35.048 --> 08:36.316
- Oh.
- All right.

08:36.316 --> 08:37.751
All right, another toast to the lovebirds.

08:37.751 --> 08:39.152
Oh.

08:39.152 --> 08:40.587
May you have as much happiness

08:40.587 --> 08:43.256
as we've had and more.

08:43.256 --> 08:45.725
Mazel tov.

08:45.725 --> 08:47.460
Thank you.

08:47.460 --> 08:49.129
I knew, you know, from the very first time

08:49.129 --> 08:50.630
I saw the two of you
together, I turned to Robert,

08:50.630 --> 08:52.665
and I said, "He's going to
propose while they're here."

08:52.665 --> 08:54.334
- Didn't I?
- Did you?

08:54.334 --> 08:55.635
- [chuckles]
- Don't...

08:55.635 --> 08:57.737
You know perfectly well that I did.

08:57.737 --> 09:00.073
I want the whole story. Tell me the story.

09:00.073 --> 09:01.307
The story?

09:01.307 --> 09:02.976
Yes, you're a writer, aren't you?

09:02.976 --> 09:06.212
I want all the details.
How did the two of you meet?

09:06.212 --> 09:07.547
Uh, well...

09:07.547 --> 09:10.083
- Uh...
- We met in Montauk.

09:10.083 --> 09:11.051
Last summer.

09:11.051 --> 09:12.519
[Yvonne] Divine.

09:12.519 --> 09:16.089
Uh, well, Noah had come to the
island to research his book.

09:16.089 --> 09:17.123
[Yvonne] Oh, of course, the book.

09:17.123 --> 09:18.491
And I was living there.

09:18.491 --> 09:20.393
I mean, I always lived there. I'm a native.

09:20.393 --> 09:23.063
And I had never met a real writer before.

09:23.063 --> 09:25.698
I was so intimidated.

09:25.698 --> 09:27.267
Probably hadn't even read a book since,

09:27.267 --> 09:29.335
I don't know, Catcher in the Rye?

09:29.335 --> 09:30.270
Really?

09:30.270 --> 09:32.038
[Alison] Mm-hmm.

09:32.038 --> 09:33.306
- So you're not a reader?
- No, not at all.

09:33.306 --> 09:34.974
Come on. Come on, that's not true.

09:34.974 --> 09:36.376
You read plenty.

09:36.376 --> 09:37.510
There are other things to do in life

09:37.510 --> 09:39.612
besides hiding behind a book.

09:39.612 --> 09:40.713
Thank you, Robert.

09:40.713 --> 09:42.982
[Yvonne] Yes, thanks so much.

09:42.982 --> 09:46.352
So, anyway, uh, there's
this little lighthouse

09:46.352 --> 09:49.522
right at the tip of the island.

09:49.522 --> 09:52.158
I think that's where we
first laid eyes on each other.

09:52.158 --> 09:53.359
Isn't it, babe?

09:53.359 --> 09:55.261
Your memory is really impressive.

09:55.261 --> 09:57.297
Well, how could I forget that?

09:57.297 --> 09:59.566
It was so romantic.

09:59.566 --> 10:03.236
That day in the rain.

10:03.236 --> 10:04.571
I'm enchanted. Go on.

10:04.571 --> 10:06.139
[sighs]

10:06.139 --> 10:09.609
Well, I was going through
a difficult time in my life.

10:09.609 --> 10:11.111
[Yvonne] Oh, no.

10:11.111 --> 10:13.379
And that day,

10:13.379 --> 10:17.584
I walked all the way out to
the lighthouse in the rain.

10:17.584 --> 10:20.687
And I was sure it'd be empty,

10:20.687 --> 10:24.687
but when I got there, I
found one other person.

10:26.693 --> 10:29.462
It was him.

10:29.462 --> 10:31.297
[Yvonne] What a beautiful story.

10:31.297 --> 10:35.101
Yes. It was somewhat unreal.

10:36.503 --> 10:39.139
What were you doing there?

10:39.139 --> 10:41.374
At the lighthouse that day in the rain.

10:41.374 --> 10:43.042
Oh, I was, um...

10:43.042 --> 10:46.112
I was researching. I was doing research.

10:46.112 --> 10:47.680
How's the book coming?

10:47.680 --> 10:49.749
It's, um... it's coming.

10:49.749 --> 10:51.718
I'd love to read it
when you want an opinion.

10:51.718 --> 10:54.988
Oh, Noah doesn't like to share
his work until it's finished.

10:54.988 --> 10:56.289
[Yvonne] Oh, I'm sorry. Of course.

10:56.289 --> 10:57.724
No, it was rude of me to ask. I'm sorry.

10:57.724 --> 11:00.059
No, no, no. Of course, no,
I could make an exception.

11:00.059 --> 11:01.594
Anyone want more wine?

11:01.594 --> 11:03.196
I've had enough. Thanks.

11:03.196 --> 11:05.131
I'd love some. Thank you.

11:05.131 --> 11:06.733
[wine pours]

11:13.606 --> 11:16.509
[Yvonne] Recognize those books?

11:16.509 --> 11:18.344
Some of them.

11:18.344 --> 11:20.046
They were all written in
the cabin you're staying in.

11:20.046 --> 11:22.248
- Really?
- Really.

11:22.248 --> 11:24.350
Since Robert and I moved
up here 20 years ago,

11:24.350 --> 11:27.220
we've hosted an author
a year, sometimes two.

11:27.220 --> 11:29.756
And most of their books
have done very, very well.

11:31.090 --> 11:32.492
[chuckles]

11:32.492 --> 11:34.427
I'm very particular about
whom I invite up here,

11:34.427 --> 11:36.095
and I don't usually take on writers

11:36.095 --> 11:38.097
I haven't personally read, but...

11:38.097 --> 11:42.035
Harry vouched so passionately for you.

11:42.035 --> 11:43.303
I tried to read your first book.

11:43.303 --> 11:44.737
I couldn't find it anywhere.

11:44.737 --> 11:47.473
That's 'cause it's out of print.

11:47.473 --> 11:48.741
Well, Harry says this second book

11:48.741 --> 11:50.443
is a big step forward anyway.

11:50.443 --> 11:52.979
I hope so. I feel kinda good about it.

11:52.979 --> 11:54.280
And you like working with Harry?

11:54.280 --> 11:55.515
Harry's great.

11:55.515 --> 11:57.383
We just can't agree on the ending,

11:57.383 --> 12:00.119
and it's driving us both a little nuts.

12:00.119 --> 12:01.988
I had a brilliant professor once tell me,

12:01.988 --> 12:04.023
"If you're having difficulty with the end,

12:04.023 --> 12:06.626
you fucked up the beginning."

12:06.626 --> 12:08.228
Oh, wonderful.

12:08.228 --> 12:09.529
I think he just meant,

12:09.529 --> 12:10.997
if you've laid all your cards out

12:10.997 --> 12:13.099
in the proper order,
the ending should flow.

12:13.099 --> 12:15.435
It should feel inevitable.

12:15.435 --> 12:17.470
At some point, fate takes over a story,

12:17.470 --> 12:21.574
and even the author himself loses control.

12:21.574 --> 12:23.209
Huh.

12:23.209 --> 12:25.211
That's, uh...

12:25.211 --> 12:27.113
never really happened to me.

12:27.113 --> 12:30.016
Tell me, what's Harry's issue with the end?

12:30.016 --> 12:32.318
Oh, I don't know, he, uh...

12:32.318 --> 12:34.053
he thinks I'm afraid to follow through

12:34.053 --> 12:36.289
on my original idea.

12:36.289 --> 12:38.258
He might be right.

12:38.258 --> 12:39.759
Would you like me to look at it?

12:39.759 --> 12:41.661
Just for another set of eyes?

12:41.661 --> 12:44.998
I wouldn't tell Harry, not even Alison.

12:44.998 --> 12:47.400
It's a very bad idea to
mix love and criticism.

12:47.400 --> 12:49.369
[laughs] Well, of course.

12:49.369 --> 12:50.670
I mean, I'd love you to.

12:50.670 --> 12:52.672
I just don't want to impose
on any more of your time.

12:52.672 --> 12:54.540
I wouldn't offer if it were an imposition.

12:54.540 --> 12:56.476
- [knock at door]
- Come in.

12:56.476 --> 12:57.710
[Yvonne] What is it, dear?

12:57.710 --> 12:59.312
Noah, can you come out here?

12:59.312 --> 13:00.613
We're in the middle of something.

13:00.613 --> 13:01.714
- I know, but...
- Well, can it wait?

13:01.714 --> 13:04.117
I don't think so.

13:04.117 --> 13:05.285
You're living in a freaking mansion?

13:05.285 --> 13:06.352
What the hell?

13:06.352 --> 13:07.220
Whitney, what are you doing here?

13:07.220 --> 13:08.454
Who's this?

13:08.454 --> 13:09.489
I'm his daughter. Who are you?

13:09.489 --> 13:11.991
Uh, Whitney, this is Yvonne, who is, uh,

13:11.991 --> 13:13.426
very generously allowing
me to stay here for a while.

13:13.426 --> 13:15.061
Yvonne, this is my daughter,

13:15.061 --> 13:17.430
who seems to have, uh,
I don't know, gone rogue.

13:17.430 --> 13:18.498
Hey, Dad, what's she doing here?

13:18.498 --> 13:20.533
I thought you weren't living together.

13:20.533 --> 13:23.303
Okay, Whit, I didn't expect you,
but you're here, so fantastic.

13:23.303 --> 13:24.737
Let's show you the cabin. Come on.

13:24.737 --> 13:26.572
Wait, ew, a cabin? Can we
just stay in your house?

13:26.572 --> 13:27.674
No. Come on. Come on. Let's go.

13:27.674 --> 13:28.741
No, why can't we just stay in this house?

13:28.741 --> 13:30.543
Can we stay here?

13:30.543 --> 13:32.178
Sorry.

13:35.548 --> 13:37.583
So what's going on, Whitney?

13:42.622 --> 13:44.324
How'd you even get here?

13:44.324 --> 13:48.194
Metro-North and then a
cab. I have street skills.

13:48.194 --> 13:50.330
Would you like something? Some water?

13:50.330 --> 13:52.298
Nice love nest.

13:52.298 --> 13:54.367
Wow, I especially like this dead fox.

13:54.367 --> 13:56.336
It's extra erotic.

13:56.336 --> 13:57.303
Does Mom know you're here?

13:57.303 --> 13:59.005
Who?

13:59.005 --> 14:00.206
Come on, cut it out.

14:00.206 --> 14:02.342
Oh, do you still call her "Mom"?

14:02.342 --> 14:04.677
Might be more appropriate
to go with a formal "Helen."

14:04.677 --> 14:07.313
Or perhaps Mrs. Solloway.
The ex-Mrs. Solloway.

14:07.313 --> 14:08.748
We're not divorced yet.

14:08.748 --> 14:11.584
Right. Hear that, Alison?
They're still married.

14:11.584 --> 14:13.519
Not like that ever stopped you.

14:13.519 --> 14:15.722
Okay, Whitney, can you at
least try to act like an adult?

14:15.722 --> 14:17.490
Sorry. I don't know any adults.

14:17.490 --> 14:18.458
How do they behave?

14:18.458 --> 14:21.594
[sighs] Whitney, just...

14:21.594 --> 14:25.594
Is that a fucking ring on her finger?

14:26.299 --> 14:28.067
Holy shit, Dad, I knew you were lame,

14:28.067 --> 14:29.736
but I didn't know you were stupid.

14:29.736 --> 14:30.737
[Noah] What are you doing?

14:30.737 --> 14:32.505
Texting Mom, your wife.

14:32.505 --> 14:34.540
- Whitney, no.
- No, stop!

14:34.540 --> 14:36.542
- [Alison] Whitney...
- Don't you fucking talk to me.

14:36.542 --> 14:38.111
Just give me that phone.
Just give me the phone!

14:38.111 --> 14:41.514
Make her take the ring
off of her fucking finger!

14:41.514 --> 14:43.649
What?

14:43.649 --> 14:46.119
You have a family. You have four kids.

14:46.119 --> 14:48.254
- I know I do. Now j...
- Then ma...

14:48.254 --> 14:50.289
- Take off the ring, bitch!
- Just stop!

14:50.289 --> 14:52.058
- [screams]
- Stop that!

14:56.662 --> 14:58.531
[Alison] I'm gonna wait outside.

15:01.200 --> 15:02.502
[sighs]

15:02.502 --> 15:06.139
[door opens and closes]

15:06.139 --> 15:08.040
Come on, Whitney.

15:11.277 --> 15:13.246
It's okay. It's all right.

15:13.246 --> 15:16.315
[crying]

15:16.315 --> 15:18.284
[crickets chirping]

15:18.284 --> 15:19.419
Here.

15:19.419 --> 15:21.020
I'm okay. Thanks.

15:25.458 --> 15:28.027
I think we're making a terrible mistake.

15:30.029 --> 15:31.531
[sighs] Please don't say that.

15:31.531 --> 15:33.299
She's right.

15:33.299 --> 15:36.269
You're not even divorced yet. Neither am I.

15:36.269 --> 15:37.537
Everything's fine here now,

15:37.537 --> 15:40.006
but what happens when we have to leave?

15:40.006 --> 15:42.542
When we actually have to
face the real world again?

15:44.343 --> 15:46.379
We'll figure it out.

15:46.379 --> 15:48.681
What if we can't?

15:48.681 --> 15:50.283
Why are you asking that?

15:50.283 --> 15:53.352
Because it's a possibility, Noah.

15:53.352 --> 15:55.121
Are you really so naive?

15:55.121 --> 15:59.158
Do you really think that things
just work out for the best?

15:59.158 --> 16:00.226
[scoffs]

16:00.226 --> 16:03.062
That true love conquers all?

16:03.062 --> 16:05.097
I can't follow you today.

16:05.097 --> 16:06.499
What does that mean?

16:06.499 --> 16:09.001
Well, one minute you're giving Yvonne

16:09.001 --> 16:11.170
some romance novel version of how we met,

16:11.170 --> 16:14.207
and now you're spouting
fucking Hegel on the deck.

16:17.510 --> 16:20.513
Did something happen while I was gone?

16:20.513 --> 16:21.581
Something you haven't told me?

16:21.581 --> 16:23.683
[chuckles]

16:23.683 --> 16:26.486
A lot of things happen
that I don't tell you.

16:33.693 --> 16:37.063
Do you really want to know things about me?

16:37.063 --> 16:41.100
Things I've never told anyone else before?

16:45.004 --> 16:48.107
[exhales] Yes.

16:48.107 --> 16:50.676
No, you don't.

16:55.248 --> 16:57.016
I slept with Oscar.

17:00.753 --> 17:01.754
Hodges?

17:01.754 --> 17:03.089
Yeah.

17:05.458 --> 17:06.425
Recently?

17:06.425 --> 17:09.595
A couple of months ago.

17:09.595 --> 17:12.598
The day you came back to Montauk actually.

17:12.598 --> 17:15.367
Okay, well...

17:15.367 --> 17:18.104
I don't love that, but it's okay.

17:18.104 --> 17:21.339
I'm not apologizing for
it. I'm just telling you.

17:21.339 --> 17:22.407
Okay.

17:29.682 --> 17:32.652
Then I tried to hurt myself.

17:32.652 --> 17:34.120
Wait, you mean you cut... you...

17:34.120 --> 17:35.988
No.

17:38.391 --> 17:40.593
I walked into the ocean.

17:42.395 --> 17:44.163
What?

17:45.998 --> 17:48.434
I wanted to drown.

17:50.503 --> 17:52.371
[sighs] Oh, God.

17:58.311 --> 18:01.447
[exhales]

18:01.447 --> 18:04.150
Come here. Come here.

18:07.453 --> 18:10.289
[kisses] Do you still feel like that?

18:13.025 --> 18:15.294
- No.
- You sure?

18:19.031 --> 18:20.766
There's nothing you can tell me

18:20.766 --> 18:23.569
that would make me give up on you.

18:23.569 --> 18:25.705
I know you don't trust a lot of people.

18:25.705 --> 18:28.174
Trust me.

18:36.549 --> 18:39.418
Cole came to visit.

18:43.122 --> 18:44.123
Here?

18:44.123 --> 18:45.491
Yeah.

18:47.360 --> 18:49.428
When?

18:49.428 --> 18:52.398
About a week ago.

18:52.398 --> 18:56.168
He came to drop off some of my things.

19:00.139 --> 19:01.307
[scoffs]

19:13.319 --> 19:17.189
I thought you said Jane
sent you those clothes.

19:18.724 --> 19:20.326
I lied.

19:25.064 --> 19:27.533
Nothing happened. We just talked.

19:38.978 --> 19:40.346
What are you doing?

19:40.346 --> 19:44.717
I'm offering you the
chance to take it back.

19:44.717 --> 19:46.052
You're a good man. You're kind.

19:46.052 --> 19:47.386
You wanna fix everyone, but I'm...

19:47.386 --> 19:49.422
Just... just stop talking for a second.

19:49.422 --> 19:51.991
I just need to think.

19:54.527 --> 19:58.364
Are you... are you trying to get rid of me?

19:58.364 --> 19:59.565
No.

19:59.565 --> 20:03.102
Are you sure?

20:03.102 --> 20:07.506
'Cause I'd understand if you were.

20:07.506 --> 20:10.643
'Cause this is scary and...

20:10.643 --> 20:12.411
perhaps insane.

20:12.411 --> 20:15.281
So, if you are,

20:15.281 --> 20:17.149
you need to tell me.

20:17.149 --> 20:18.250
Just say it.

20:21.020 --> 20:23.723
Neither of us is perfect, Alison,

20:23.723 --> 20:25.357
and there are many, many things that I wish

20:25.357 --> 20:27.259
I had handled differently.

20:31.230 --> 20:33.399
And God knows we could
spend the rest of our lives

20:33.399 --> 20:36.368
judging each other, but that's
not how I want to live anymore.

20:38.037 --> 20:39.638
My whole life, I've been afraid

20:39.638 --> 20:41.507
of what other people
think of me, and I'm done.

20:41.507 --> 20:43.576
I'm just done.

20:47.413 --> 20:51.450
I want to start my life over again.

20:51.450 --> 20:54.019
With you.

20:54.019 --> 20:55.488
So, if you're not ready for that,

20:55.488 --> 20:57.757
then just, for Christ's sake,

20:57.757 --> 21:00.292
just be decent and tell me.

21:02.161 --> 21:05.164
'Cause I'm not fucking around with you.

21:05.164 --> 21:08.134
[♪ soft music ♪]

21:08.134 --> 21:12.134
♪♪♪

21:17.009 --> 21:18.310
[sighs]

21:26.385 --> 21:28.287
I don't want to go home.

21:34.693 --> 21:37.329
I hate it there.

21:37.329 --> 21:39.532
Between Grandma and Mom, it's like

21:39.532 --> 21:43.532
I live in a coven of depressed witches.

21:44.136 --> 21:47.239
I honestly think it might
be affecting my schoolwork.

21:47.239 --> 21:48.274
That's not true.

21:48.274 --> 21:50.042
Yes, it is.

21:50.042 --> 21:53.479
It's like a fucking graveyard, Dad.

21:54.713 --> 21:58.450
I want to come live with you.

21:58.450 --> 22:01.554
Well, I want you to be able
to live with me too sometimes.

22:01.554 --> 22:04.323
No, not sometimes. Permanently.

22:07.459 --> 22:10.462
Okay, Whitney, well, I may
need your help with that.

22:14.033 --> 22:16.135
I have to ask a favor.

22:18.204 --> 22:20.372
Don't tell Mom.

22:22.708 --> 22:24.143
Yeah.

22:26.579 --> 22:29.682
I think it'd be a mistake.

22:29.682 --> 22:33.118
We're going into mediation, and...

22:33.118 --> 22:36.455
I'm doing everything I
can to create a situation

22:36.455 --> 22:37.690
where you can live with me,

22:37.690 --> 22:41.360
at least part of the time.

22:41.360 --> 22:43.696
But in order for us to
do that, to find a way...

22:43.696 --> 22:46.298
She can't know you're engaged to Alison.

22:46.298 --> 22:50.202
She can't know I'm living with Alison.

22:50.202 --> 22:53.339
Don't worry, Dad. I got you.

23:02.314 --> 23:04.216
Hey.

23:04.216 --> 23:07.052
- Noah Solloway.
- How are you, man?

23:07.052 --> 23:08.153
Oh, I thought we'd lost you, brother.

23:08.153 --> 23:09.355
Nearly did.

23:09.355 --> 23:11.991
Heard about that acquisition, you fuck.

23:11.991 --> 23:12.992
Congratulations.

23:12.992 --> 23:15.160
Yeah. [sharp exhale]

23:15.160 --> 23:17.396
- Pretty big deal.
- Yeah? How much did you make?

23:17.396 --> 23:19.999
Uh, my abacus broke.

23:19.999 --> 23:20.766
I don't wanna know.

23:20.766 --> 23:22.468
Yeah, you really don't.

23:22.468 --> 23:24.370
How long has it been
since I've seen you, man?

23:24.370 --> 23:26.238
Is it, like, a year?

23:26.238 --> 23:27.373
Come on, no. Six months? Not even.

23:27.373 --> 23:30.142
- Is it? I don't know.
- Well...

23:30.142 --> 23:31.210
I guess time moves more slowly when you're

23:31.210 --> 23:32.711
[whispers] a gazillionaire.

23:32.711 --> 23:35.114
- You're such an asshole.
- I am an asshole.

23:35.114 --> 23:37.249
Uh, just coffee for me. Thanks.

23:37.249 --> 23:38.350
- Sure.
- Thank you.

23:38.350 --> 23:39.585
Mm-hmm.

23:39.585 --> 23:42.121
[laughs] Why don't you get her number?

23:42.121 --> 23:43.422
Tell her how rich you are.

23:43.422 --> 23:45.157
Ah, nah, man. Waitresses are your thing.

23:45.157 --> 23:47.226
Ah. Touché.

23:47.226 --> 23:48.427
Actually, I started seeing someone.

23:48.427 --> 23:50.529
- Really? Since when?
- Mm.

23:50.529 --> 23:54.033
It's recent, but I think
it might be getting serious.

23:54.033 --> 23:55.401
When do I get to meet her?

23:55.401 --> 23:56.735
Oh, I don't think we're ready for that yet,

23:56.735 --> 23:59.271
but it's exciting.

23:59.271 --> 24:01.540
That's wonderful. I'm really happy for you.

24:03.208 --> 24:04.743
Sometimes you just get
lucky. How about you?

24:04.743 --> 24:06.412
Oh, I'm good.

24:06.412 --> 24:08.347
I'm just, uh, you know, getting divorced.

24:11.317 --> 24:13.419
You know what, Noah, I'm sorry.

24:13.419 --> 24:15.421
I am. I really thought
that you would work it out.

24:15.421 --> 24:18.023
I know, but it's for
the best. It really is.

24:18.023 --> 24:19.291
I mean, Helen will be fine.

24:19.291 --> 24:22.061
She's gonna be single for about 30 seconds.

24:22.061 --> 24:24.129
The kids will all pull through.

24:24.129 --> 24:25.631
And I'm feeling good.

24:25.631 --> 24:27.466
- Better than I have in years.
- Good.

24:27.466 --> 24:29.268
Just need to figure out a
way to afford an apartment,

24:29.268 --> 24:31.437
so I can get co-custody of the kids and...

24:31.437 --> 24:33.172
How's the book coming? I
heard you got a big advance.

24:33.172 --> 24:34.273
No, it's good. I...

24:34.273 --> 24:35.741
They only give you like 20% up front.

24:35.741 --> 24:37.977
They keep the rest until
you turn in the book, so...

24:37.977 --> 24:39.712
You almost done?

24:39.712 --> 24:41.080
I'm having trouble with the ending.

24:41.080 --> 24:42.214
- Hmm.
- It'll be fine.

24:42.214 --> 24:44.049
I'm working it out.

24:44.049 --> 24:45.317
Good.

24:47.119 --> 24:48.454
What are you doing?

24:48.454 --> 24:51.290
I am sending an email to my accountant

24:51.290 --> 24:54.159
and telling him to send you $50,000.

24:54.159 --> 24:55.761
Come on, Max. Come on.

24:55.761 --> 24:58.063
- Are you insane?
- It's not a loan.

24:58.063 --> 24:59.465
- It's a gift, okay?
- I... no.

24:59.465 --> 25:00.566
I don't want to take
any more money off you.

25:00.566 --> 25:02.334
Noah, take it. I can afford it. Believe me.

25:02.334 --> 25:03.502
No, it's too mu... Max, come on.

25:03.502 --> 25:06.071
I want to help you.

25:06.071 --> 25:09.641
Look, the sooner you
and Helen get divorced,

25:09.641 --> 25:12.211
the happier everyone will be.

25:15.247 --> 25:16.215
Done.

25:16.215 --> 25:18.317
[laughs] You're a mensch.

25:18.317 --> 25:20.285
[laughs]

25:20.285 --> 25:22.488
- Thank you, sweetheart.
- You're welcome.

25:23.689 --> 25:25.624
Thank you.

25:31.463 --> 25:33.365
[knock at door]

25:35.434 --> 25:37.069
[door handle jiggles, door rattles]

25:40.105 --> 25:41.640
[doorbell buzzes]

25:44.276 --> 25:46.111
Anybody there?

25:48.981 --> 25:50.516
Are you Noah Solloway?

25:50.516 --> 25:52.518
I am. Do you work here?
I have an appointment.

25:52.518 --> 25:54.253
I'm here on behalf of attorney Jon Gottlief

25:54.253 --> 25:56.255
and his client Helen Solloway.

25:56.255 --> 25:57.990
This is an action for divorce.

25:57.990 --> 26:00.059
You're being served.

26:03.362 --> 26:06.398
- [♪ soft instrumentals ♪]
- _

26:06.398 --> 26:08.400
♪♪♪

26:08.400 --> 26:11.437
[laughter]

26:13.439 --> 26:16.208
[Yvonne] How about another
toast to the happy couple?

26:16.208 --> 26:18.410
To your future and your life together,

26:18.410 --> 26:20.079
which is just beginning.

26:20.079 --> 26:23.082
- Thank you.
- Alison, more wine?

26:23.082 --> 26:25.517
Oh, uh, no. Thank you. I've had enough.

26:25.517 --> 26:27.152
I've always wanted a
wedding on this property.

26:27.152 --> 26:28.420
[Robert] Yvonne...

26:28.420 --> 26:29.621
I thought our daughter
would be married here,

26:29.621 --> 26:32.357
but in the end, she wanted
a destination wedding,

26:32.357 --> 26:34.226
so we all traipsed off to Provence,

26:34.226 --> 26:36.562
which, of course, is exactly
like here, only more expensive.

26:36.562 --> 26:38.664
- Provence was your idea.
- No, it was not.

26:38.664 --> 26:40.699
I distinctly remember it being your idea.

26:40.699 --> 26:43.335
Only because it became obvious
that's what Mellie wanted.

26:43.335 --> 26:44.970
I was just trying to be a good mother.

26:44.970 --> 26:47.039
Anyway, I'm just offering, you know.

26:47.039 --> 26:49.274
- Something to think about.
- No, thank you.

26:49.274 --> 26:52.377
Uh, we haven't even set a date yet.

26:52.377 --> 26:54.680
- We...
- Well, there's no rush.

26:54.680 --> 26:56.215
Unless, of course, you're pregnant.

26:56.215 --> 26:57.416
- [Yvonne laughs]
- Yvonne!

26:57.416 --> 26:59.685
Oh, uh, no. No. We're not... we're not...

26:59.685 --> 27:01.587
No, I'm... [stammers]

27:01.587 --> 27:04.289
I already have four kids
from my first marriage, so...

27:04.289 --> 27:05.557
- Four kids?
- Yeah.

27:05.557 --> 27:07.192
- So I think I'm done.
- Wow.

27:07.192 --> 27:09.595
Or at least, I...

27:11.763 --> 27:13.732
She doesn't seem as certain as you, Noah.

27:13.732 --> 27:15.701
[Robert] Yvonne, please, enough.

27:15.701 --> 27:18.103
This is obscene. Leave them alone.

27:18.103 --> 27:20.172
You should just do it,
you know, if you want to.

27:20.172 --> 27:22.374
Men always say no to a
baby, and then in the end,

27:22.374 --> 27:24.243
they're thrilled and take
credit for the whole idea.

27:24.243 --> 27:25.978
- That's it.
- Hey, hey.

27:25.978 --> 27:27.279
- Hey.
- That's the 2005.

27:27.279 --> 27:30.115
- Noah, are you through?
- Yeah.

27:30.115 --> 27:31.450
No, Robert, please. Let me.

27:31.450 --> 27:32.584
Noah, this would be a perfect time

27:32.584 --> 27:34.453
to have a little chat about the book.

27:34.453 --> 27:36.121
Want to join me in the living room?

27:38.290 --> 27:41.026
It's okay. Go.

27:41.026 --> 27:42.227
Thanks.

27:48.367 --> 27:50.169
- You're a pro.
- [laughs]

27:50.169 --> 27:52.204
I used to be a waitress.

27:52.204 --> 27:54.373
[indistinct chatter]

27:54.373 --> 27:56.175
[Yvonne laughs]

27:56.175 --> 27:58.744
Book people, so snooty.

28:05.050 --> 28:06.618
So you're not a book person?

28:06.618 --> 28:10.122
Not really. I can't sit still.

28:10.122 --> 28:12.658
I'd rather just be outdoors. [chuckles]

28:15.027 --> 28:17.629
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.
Don't do that. Don't do that.

28:17.629 --> 28:20.632
Salmon skin. I'll take it.
Here, put it in the bag.

28:20.632 --> 28:22.434
What do you want it for?

28:22.434 --> 28:24.403
Can you keep a secret?

28:25.671 --> 28:27.039
Sure, I guess.

28:27.039 --> 28:28.473
You can't tell Yvonne.

28:28.473 --> 28:30.976
[chuckles] Tell Yvonne what?

28:30.976 --> 28:33.245
It's for our dog.

28:33.245 --> 28:34.980
- You have a dog?
- Yup.

28:34.980 --> 28:37.216
His name's Pete.

28:37.216 --> 28:38.717
He's part wolf.

28:41.353 --> 28:43.021
Well, where is he?

28:43.021 --> 28:45.123
Yeah, I don't know.

28:45.123 --> 28:46.592
[laughs] Okay.

28:46.592 --> 28:49.528
He ran away a few weeks
ago. Yvonne was thrilled.

28:49.528 --> 28:51.430
She's hated him ever
since I brought him home.

28:51.430 --> 28:52.998
She thought he was dangerous.

28:52.998 --> 28:54.633
Was he?

28:54.633 --> 28:56.368
He snapped at our grandson once,

28:56.368 --> 28:58.437
but I-I think he's just misunderstood.

28:58.437 --> 29:01.506
He was never meant to sleep
in a kennel or walk on a leash.

29:01.506 --> 29:04.309
He needs to run free. So now...

29:04.309 --> 29:06.979
I leave little scraps
of food outside for him

29:06.979 --> 29:09.281
when I get a chance, just
so he doesn't go hungry.

29:09.281 --> 29:11.350
[both laugh]

29:11.350 --> 29:12.417
- Remember...
- Yeah.

29:12.417 --> 29:14.353
- ...it's a secret.
- Mm-hmm.

29:14.353 --> 29:16.288
- Ow!
- Be careful with your knee.

29:16.288 --> 29:17.356
Yeah, yeah.

29:19.124 --> 29:20.392
[chuckles]

29:20.392 --> 29:21.727
[Whitney] Hello?

29:21.727 --> 29:24.630
Dad, hello?

29:29.134 --> 29:32.204
Whitney.

29:32.204 --> 29:33.705
What are you doing here?

29:36.174 --> 29:38.076
Boom.

29:38.076 --> 29:40.312
Ruby owes me 50 bucks.

29:43.382 --> 29:45.651
She's a stupid fucking waitress,

29:45.651 --> 29:48.220
and she's also a slut and she's a liar,

29:48.220 --> 29:50.589
and she destroyed our entire family!

29:50.589 --> 29:52.324
[Noah] You're being melodramatic.

29:52.324 --> 29:55.193
[Whitney] Oh! Oh! Okay, really? Am I?

29:55.193 --> 29:58.196
Did you know that my dad
moved to bumblefuck New York

29:58.196 --> 30:00.732
with his bimbo girlfriend
after he cheated on my mom

30:00.732 --> 30:03.602
and left her with four
kids to raise by herself?

30:03.602 --> 30:05.537
Maybe I'm being melodramatic 'cause I live

30:05.537 --> 30:07.005
in a fucking melodrama!

30:07.005 --> 30:08.707
[Noah] Calm down, Whitney.

30:08.707 --> 30:11.543
Fuck you! Okay?

30:11.543 --> 30:15.543
You don't even know her, Dad.
You know nothing about her.

30:16.315 --> 30:19.484
You're leaving our family
for a total stranger!

30:19.484 --> 30:21.586
[continues indistinctly]

30:21.586 --> 30:24.656
[♪ melancholy music ♪]

30:24.656 --> 30:28.656
♪♪♪

30:46.211 --> 30:47.479
[sighs]

30:50.349 --> 30:53.251
[crickets chirping]

30:58.390 --> 31:00.425
Is it safe?

31:00.425 --> 31:03.228
Jesus Christ, you scared me.

31:03.228 --> 31:04.763
Sorry.

31:09.067 --> 31:11.370
[sighs]

31:11.370 --> 31:13.071
Where is she?

31:13.071 --> 31:15.273
She's smoking a cigarette right over there.

31:24.216 --> 31:26.118
I don't know what to do.

31:27.552 --> 31:29.254
It's okay.

31:36.561 --> 31:39.698
You know she Uber'd here from the city?

31:39.698 --> 31:42.434
Gonna cost me 200 bucks.

31:46.371 --> 31:48.373
Where is she gonna sleep tonight?

31:48.373 --> 31:51.710
I don't fucking know.

31:51.710 --> 31:54.146
Probably our bed.

31:54.146 --> 31:55.480
[sighs]

31:55.480 --> 31:58.984
Where are we gonna sleep?

31:58.984 --> 32:01.620
You can have the couch.
I'll... I'll take the rug.

32:11.997 --> 32:15.167
[sighs] Do you think
we're making a mistake?

32:21.206 --> 32:23.008
Do you?

32:26.211 --> 32:28.146
Do you want this back?

32:31.149 --> 32:33.151
No. I...

32:33.151 --> 32:35.287
No, I want you to keep it.

32:42.461 --> 32:45.063
It's so easy when they're young.

32:46.765 --> 32:50.469
All they need is food and sleep and hugs.

32:50.469 --> 32:53.405
And they think you're a god.

32:53.405 --> 32:56.174
Why do they ever have to grow up?

33:07.185 --> 33:09.988
What's the worst thing you've ever done?

33:14.459 --> 33:16.728
This, probably.

33:20.465 --> 33:22.968
How about you?

33:22.968 --> 33:25.604
[waves lapping softly]

33:25.604 --> 33:28.673
[♪ melancholy music ♪]

33:28.673 --> 33:32.673
♪♪♪

33:39.317 --> 33:41.219
I've done a lot of things.

33:51.630 --> 33:53.665
[slam]

33:55.200 --> 33:57.135
[clattering]

33:57.135 --> 33:58.603
[Whitney] Oh, hey.

33:58.603 --> 34:00.572
Morning.

34:00.572 --> 34:02.474
I'm making eggs. Do you want any?

34:02.474 --> 34:04.476
Uh, sure.

34:04.476 --> 34:08.013
[sizzling]

34:08.013 --> 34:10.748
Uh, where's your dad?

34:10.748 --> 34:13.351
Oh, he went outside to try
to find some cell service,

34:13.351 --> 34:15.053
so he could call us a cab.

34:15.053 --> 34:16.321
How do you take it?

34:16.321 --> 34:19.257
Oh, uh, black's great. Thanks.

34:22.327 --> 34:24.696
Look, Whitney, I just want you to know

34:24.696 --> 34:27.465
I'm not into the whole
wicked stepmother thing, okay?

34:30.135 --> 34:33.138
I... I just want to be your friend.

34:38.643 --> 34:39.643
[silverware clatters]

34:39.643 --> 34:41.379
Here you go.

34:41.379 --> 34:43.681
- Do you want toast?
- Wow. Uh, no, thanks.

34:43.681 --> 34:45.583
I'm okay.

34:46.650 --> 34:48.386
Aren't you gonna have any?

34:48.386 --> 34:50.088
Oh, please, breakfast? Gross.

34:51.322 --> 34:52.591
[chuckles]

34:54.993 --> 34:56.695
Mmm.

34:56.695 --> 34:59.698
Friend, can I ask you
a very friendly favor?

34:59.698 --> 35:02.634
Of course.

35:02.634 --> 35:04.703
Can I please have Scott Lockhart's number?

35:04.703 --> 35:07.272
- What?
- Scott's number.

35:07.272 --> 35:09.007
He changed it. And his address too.

35:09.007 --> 35:10.542
Don't you have a restraining order

35:10.542 --> 35:12.077
- against Scotty now?
- No, no, no, no, no.

35:12.077 --> 35:14.312
That's not a real thing.
My grandmother did that.

35:14.312 --> 35:17.015
No, I'm pretty sure
that's a very real thing.

35:17.015 --> 35:20.118
- Not to me.
- To the police.

35:20.118 --> 35:21.686
[scoffs]

35:21.686 --> 35:23.321
Well, you know what? Fuck you, friend.

35:23.321 --> 35:25.557
- Forget I asked.
- Wait, Whitney, I'm sorry.

35:25.557 --> 35:27.425
I ju... [chuckles]

35:27.425 --> 35:29.661
I-I don't get why you want
to get in touch with Scotty

35:29.661 --> 35:31.096
after everything that happened.

35:31.096 --> 35:32.631
Because I love him.

35:35.600 --> 35:38.169
Like you love my father, right?

35:39.671 --> 35:41.506
- [chuckles] It's...
- Well...

35:41.506 --> 35:44.175
Well, don't you?

35:44.175 --> 35:46.177
I do love your father. Yes.

35:46.177 --> 35:49.047
Okay... then you understand,

35:49.047 --> 35:51.049
and you'll get me Scotty's number.

35:53.051 --> 35:55.053
- I can't, Whitney. I'm sorry.
- Why not?

35:55.053 --> 35:57.722
It's not appropriate.

35:57.722 --> 35:59.591
[laughs]

35:59.591 --> 36:02.193
Are you fucking kidding me?

36:02.193 --> 36:04.462
You want to talk to me
about what's "appropriate"?

36:04.462 --> 36:08.066
Okay. Why don't we ask
your dad what he thinks?

36:08.066 --> 36:10.468
You are a very disappointing person.

36:10.468 --> 36:13.038
[door opens]

36:13.038 --> 36:14.339
Hey, Daddy. Good morning.

36:14.339 --> 36:16.608
Hey, kiddo. You get some breakfast?

36:16.608 --> 36:18.476
Yup, I'm all full.

36:18.476 --> 36:21.446
Okay, we need to go if
we want to get this train.

36:21.446 --> 36:23.348
See you later.

36:28.620 --> 36:30.622
Call me.

36:30.622 --> 36:33.658
[♪ curious music ♪]

36:33.658 --> 36:37.658
♪♪♪

36:42.367 --> 36:44.135
[sighs]

36:45.437 --> 36:47.072
Oh, hey.

36:47.072 --> 36:48.707
So you want me to arrange these manuscripts

36:48.707 --> 36:50.208
chronologically, right?

36:50.208 --> 36:52.577
So should I go by the
date on the cover or...

36:52.577 --> 36:54.245
That can wait.

36:54.245 --> 36:56.648
I need to know what happened last night.

36:56.648 --> 36:59.484
So that's Noah's daughter?

36:59.484 --> 37:01.753
That's his oldest, yes.

37:01.753 --> 37:03.455
She seems like a holy terror.

37:03.455 --> 37:05.256
Ugh, she's a teenager.

37:05.256 --> 37:08.226
So? I never let my
daughter behave that way.

37:08.226 --> 37:12.030
- Well, I'm not her mother.
- No, of course not.

37:12.030 --> 37:13.465
[car door shuts, engine starts]

37:13.465 --> 37:15.433
Still, it looks like

37:15.433 --> 37:17.502
you're gonna have your
work cut out for you.

37:17.502 --> 37:19.671
[car pulls away]

37:19.671 --> 37:21.639
What in the world?

37:21.639 --> 37:24.609
Why is Hugo leaving? He just got here.

37:24.609 --> 37:26.578
- Ugh. Robert?
- Hmm?

37:26.578 --> 37:28.580
Why did Hugo just drive off?

37:28.580 --> 37:30.515
- I fired him.
- What? Why?

37:30.515 --> 37:32.183
He said something that offended me.

37:32.183 --> 37:33.585
What are you talking
about? What did he say?

37:33.585 --> 37:35.286
He said I would need six more
months of physical therapy.

37:35.286 --> 37:37.522
Oh, honey, I don't have the time for this.

37:37.522 --> 37:39.457
[Yvonne] I already raised our child.

37:39.457 --> 37:41.092
I do not have the energy to raise you.

37:41.092 --> 37:42.694
- [cell phone ringing]
- Okay.

37:42.694 --> 37:46.231
If that's Hugo, I'm telling
him to come right back.

37:46.231 --> 37:49.534
Hello? Oh, hi, Marilyn.

37:49.534 --> 37:51.136
What happened?

37:51.136 --> 37:53.138
- Oh, my God.
- What?

37:53.138 --> 37:54.672
Oh, you're kidding.

37:54.672 --> 37:56.307
Marilyn, I'm so sorry.

37:56.307 --> 37:59.177
Yeah... we'll deal with this right away.

37:59.177 --> 38:01.212
- Be in touch.
- What happened?

38:01.212 --> 38:03.248
[sighs] A massacre.

38:03.248 --> 38:06.151
Marilyn's chickens.
Every one of them, dead.

38:06.151 --> 38:08.453
A dog got into the chicken coop.

38:08.453 --> 38:10.288
Marilyn swears it was Pete.

38:10.288 --> 38:12.524
Impossible. Pete's gone.

38:12.524 --> 38:14.192
Well, he hasn't gone very far.

38:14.192 --> 38:15.627
Apparently he's somewhere very close by,

38:15.627 --> 38:17.495
perpetrating a chicken holocaust.

38:17.495 --> 38:19.330
What would you like me to do?

38:19.330 --> 38:22.167
Call the dog catcher like
you said you would weeks ago.

38:22.167 --> 38:23.501
They'll just put him down if they find him.

38:23.501 --> 38:25.403
Which is exactly what needs to happen.

38:25.403 --> 38:27.272
Well, maybe if you hadn't
kicked him out of the house,

38:27.272 --> 38:28.573
he wouldn't have to go eat
other people's chickens.

38:28.573 --> 38:30.175
Kicked him out? Robert, your dog ran away.

38:30.175 --> 38:33.178
Because you made him feel so unwelcome!

38:33.178 --> 38:35.146
Alison, do me a favor.

38:35.146 --> 38:38.082
- Find me a local dog catcher.
- No! Stop!

38:38.082 --> 38:41.186
[Robert] This is ridiculous.

38:43.254 --> 38:45.056
I'll do it.

38:45.056 --> 38:47.192
I'll go kill my own dog.

38:47.192 --> 38:49.027
Will that make you happy, Yvonne?

38:49.027 --> 38:50.328
Extremely.

38:52.463 --> 38:55.333
Alison, which one of us do
you think is the crazier?

38:57.302 --> 38:58.503
Uh...

38:58.503 --> 39:00.972
You, obviously. Otherwise she'd answer.

39:00.972 --> 39:02.507
You're going now?

39:02.507 --> 39:05.210
No time like the present
to execute your best friend!

39:05.210 --> 39:06.711
I thought I was your best friend.

39:06.711 --> 39:08.279
[Robert groans]

39:08.279 --> 39:10.148
Alison, go with him, so
he doesn't hurt his knee.

39:10.148 --> 39:12.417
- I'll be fine!
- No, you won't!

39:12.417 --> 39:13.718
Do you mind?

39:13.718 --> 39:16.221
No. No, not at all. I'll...

39:16.221 --> 39:18.456
When you get back, could you help him

39:18.456 --> 39:20.358
with those exercises [lowers
voice] he refuses to do?

39:20.358 --> 39:22.527
- Of course.
- Thank you.

39:22.527 --> 39:24.696
All right, I'm going to
go read the fourth draft

39:24.696 --> 39:27.065
of a memoir about surviving a tsunami.

39:27.065 --> 39:28.700
Needless to say, do not disturb me.

39:31.736 --> 39:33.071
You ready for this?

39:34.505 --> 39:37.542
[♪ pensive music ♪]

39:37.542 --> 39:41.542
♪♪♪

39:47.485 --> 39:49.988
[hawk cries]

39:49.988 --> 39:51.689
Look, it's a hawk.

39:51.689 --> 39:54.559
[hawk cries]

39:58.563 --> 40:02.000
There are two of them on our property.

40:02.000 --> 40:03.968
They mate for life.

40:09.240 --> 40:11.743
You must be pretty excited.

40:11.743 --> 40:13.578
About what?

40:13.578 --> 40:15.213
Getting married.

40:15.213 --> 40:16.681
Oh.

40:18.650 --> 40:22.387
Or maybe just getting cold feet, huh?

40:22.387 --> 40:23.988
I don't know.

40:23.988 --> 40:27.425
I guess it's important to Noah, but...

40:27.425 --> 40:29.394
I don't need to get married again.

40:29.394 --> 40:31.362
Again?

40:31.362 --> 40:33.665
Uh, yeah.

40:33.665 --> 40:35.767
I was married before too.

40:35.767 --> 40:37.502
Wow. You're so young.

40:37.502 --> 40:40.538
I'm not that young.

40:40.538 --> 40:42.974
We got married right after college.

40:42.974 --> 40:45.977
Didn't pan out?

40:45.977 --> 40:49.314
Not exactly.

40:49.314 --> 40:50.982
My first marriage fell apart.

40:50.982 --> 40:52.250
Don't let it scare ya.

40:52.250 --> 40:54.018
You just gotta get back on the horse.

40:54.018 --> 40:55.586
Right.

40:55.586 --> 40:57.155
That's what they say.

40:57.155 --> 40:58.556
Oh, you don't believe me?

41:07.598 --> 41:11.598
The thing is, I had a
child with my first husband.

41:12.570 --> 41:15.707
He's... he's dead now. He, uh... he died.

41:17.675 --> 41:19.310
What?

41:19.310 --> 41:22.246
Yeah. He... yeah.

41:24.649 --> 41:26.351
Oh, no.

41:27.685 --> 41:30.188
- You poor kid.
- [sighs]

41:30.188 --> 41:32.156
Right, so...

41:32.156 --> 41:33.558
the thought of doing this again

41:33.558 --> 41:36.494
with somebody who didn't
know Gabriel just...

41:36.494 --> 41:39.063
That was his name? Your son?

41:45.203 --> 41:46.637
Hmm.

41:54.612 --> 41:56.280
[sighs]

42:02.653 --> 42:06.424
Do you mind if I ask how he died?

42:06.424 --> 42:07.692
Uh, no. No.

42:07.692 --> 42:09.994
Um...

42:09.994 --> 42:12.296
he died of something
called secondary drowning.

42:12.296 --> 42:13.231
Hmm.

42:13.231 --> 42:16.200
It's very rare.

42:16.200 --> 42:18.970
Children go swimming, and they...

42:18.970 --> 42:21.172
accidentally swallow too much water.

42:21.172 --> 42:23.107
- And then later...
- Oh.

42:28.179 --> 42:30.348
I didn't know how sick he was,

42:30.348 --> 42:34.118
and I didn't take him to the hospital.

42:34.118 --> 42:36.254
He died in his sleep.

42:40.558 --> 42:42.260
And so you carry that with you.

42:42.260 --> 42:43.995
Yeah, I do. Yeah.

42:50.101 --> 42:51.436
That's, uh...

42:55.473 --> 42:57.675
That's the worst thing in the world, kid.

43:00.711 --> 43:02.080
[exhales]

43:02.080 --> 43:03.981
And your Noah, he knows all this?

43:03.981 --> 43:05.983
Uh...

43:05.983 --> 43:08.019
some of it.

43:08.019 --> 43:09.487
Well...

43:15.193 --> 43:16.694
What you got there?

43:16.694 --> 43:18.729
Oh, uh...

43:18.729 --> 43:21.699
it's Gabriel's stone.

43:21.699 --> 43:23.634
He was a worrier. [laughs, sniffles]

43:23.634 --> 43:24.969
A really sensitive kid.

43:24.969 --> 43:26.504
So...

43:26.504 --> 43:28.272
we used to go down to the beach,

43:28.272 --> 43:30.208
and we'd collect these rocks

43:30.208 --> 43:33.044
that the waves had carved
a little pocket into.

43:35.179 --> 43:37.548
And I told him, whenever he was worried,

43:37.548 --> 43:40.551
he just had to rub the rock
and everything would be fine.

43:45.189 --> 43:48.559
He believed me.

43:48.559 --> 43:51.596
[crying]

43:57.668 --> 43:59.604
- You okay?
- Yeah.

44:01.038 --> 44:03.074
[sighs]

44:04.342 --> 44:07.411
I just thought that if... [exhales]

44:07.411 --> 44:09.614
I could go somewhere else or...

44:09.614 --> 44:12.183
be with somebody else, then...

44:16.387 --> 44:18.523
But it doesn't ever leave you.

44:21.592 --> 44:23.327
And Noah doesn't understand.

44:23.327 --> 44:25.530
I mean, he wants to, but he can't.

44:29.066 --> 44:31.502
Let me ask you something.
You love this guy?

44:33.037 --> 44:34.739
Very much.

44:34.739 --> 44:37.608
I made this mistake with my first wife.

44:37.608 --> 44:41.608
Uh, I wanted her to
understand everything about me.

44:42.547 --> 44:45.683
When she didn't, that
she had failed me somehow,

44:45.683 --> 44:47.385
that it wasn't "true love."

44:47.385 --> 44:49.487
[chuckles]

44:51.489 --> 44:54.091
You've obviously been dealt a brutal hand,

44:54.091 --> 44:58.763
and he may never be able
to fully appreciate it,

44:58.763 --> 45:01.232
but there'll always be something about him

45:01.232 --> 45:03.401
that baffles you.

45:04.435 --> 45:07.238
Being alive is, essentially,

45:07.238 --> 45:10.074
a very lonely proposition.

45:11.442 --> 45:14.645
You have to mostly carry your pack alone.

45:14.645 --> 45:18.249
Nobody gets as much help as they need.

45:22.220 --> 45:25.523
But in marriage, things get less lonely.

45:25.523 --> 45:27.558
Just a little, but...

45:27.558 --> 45:29.527
it makes a big difference.

45:31.596 --> 45:33.431
[chuckles]

45:36.400 --> 45:39.403
[howling]

45:41.539 --> 45:43.241
That's him.

45:45.109 --> 45:46.644
That's Pete.

45:49.113 --> 45:51.549
Pete!

45:51.549 --> 45:54.218
Come here!

45:54.218 --> 45:56.687
[chuckles]

45:56.687 --> 45:59.290
[laughing] Hey. Hey!

45:59.290 --> 46:01.659
Where are ya? Oh, there you go!

46:01.659 --> 46:04.228
Hey! Hey!

46:04.228 --> 46:07.164
Hey, hey, hey. Yeah. Yeah.

46:07.164 --> 46:10.234
You old rascal. Yeah.

46:10.234 --> 46:12.036
Yeah. Come here. Come here.

46:14.038 --> 46:16.540
[Pete grunting softly]

46:16.540 --> 46:19.543
I'm gonna have to kill ya, Petey.

46:19.543 --> 46:22.146
You've become a menace to society.

46:25.049 --> 46:28.085
[♪ dramatic music ♪]

46:28.085 --> 46:31.155
♪♪♪

46:31.155 --> 46:33.224
[Pete whines]

46:34.458 --> 46:38.458
♪♪♪

46:44.168 --> 46:46.070
[gunshot] [Pete yelps]

46:57.181 --> 46:58.716
[sighs]

47:03.187 --> 47:05.089
[exhales sharply]

47:16.067 --> 47:17.068
- Hey.
- Oof.

47:17.068 --> 47:18.069
Here. Oh.

47:18.069 --> 47:19.637
- [chuckles]
- Yeah.

47:19.637 --> 47:20.738
Thanks.

47:20.738 --> 47:23.107
I heard the gunshot. Did you get him?

47:24.575 --> 47:26.744
Robert, I said, did you get him?

47:29.246 --> 47:30.281
I got him.

47:30.281 --> 47:33.751
So he's dead?

47:33.751 --> 47:37.221
He's dead. And I need a drink.

47:48.165 --> 47:51.035
Was it very gruesome?

47:51.035 --> 47:52.403
No.

47:52.403 --> 47:55.539
It was sort of... beautiful.

47:59.243 --> 48:00.978
I...

48:03.647 --> 48:06.650
[♪ tense music ♪]

48:06.650 --> 48:10.650
♪♪♪

48:19.363 --> 48:21.665
[takes a deep breath]

48:21.665 --> 48:25.665
♪♪♪

49:25.129 --> 49:28.165
[♪ gentle music ♪]

49:28.165 --> 49:32.165
♪♪♪

50:41.071 --> 50:44.108
[moaning]

51:03.727 --> 51:05.195
[Noah sighs]

51:15.706 --> 51:16.740
[sighs]

51:16.740 --> 51:18.576
What can I get you both?

51:18.576 --> 51:21.145
Coffee? Tea? Whiskey?

51:21.145 --> 51:23.514
- I'll take a double.
- He's kidding.

51:23.514 --> 51:25.683
- I'm kidding.
- I'm not.

51:25.683 --> 51:28.152
Luke?

51:28.152 --> 51:29.753
Uh, he will have a Jamison's.

51:29.753 --> 51:31.522
- On the rocks?
- Sure.

51:31.522 --> 51:32.556
Be generous.

51:32.556 --> 51:35.392
And for the lady, a chamomile tea?

51:35.392 --> 51:37.661
Wild guess.

51:37.661 --> 51:39.029
Fine. Thank you.

51:39.029 --> 51:40.230
[Luke] Coming right up.

51:40.230 --> 51:42.099
Good. Sit, sit.

51:44.368 --> 51:46.270
[clears throat]

51:47.438 --> 51:48.606
Thanks.

51:48.606 --> 51:50.140
So let's get right to it, folks.

51:50.140 --> 51:52.109
My time is expensive.

51:52.109 --> 51:53.210
First thing we gotta do is get this case

51:53.210 --> 51:54.578
moved out of Montauk.

51:54.578 --> 51:56.146
They fucking hate you there.

51:56.146 --> 51:57.214
There's no way you'll get a fair trial.

51:57.214 --> 51:58.415
Can you do that?

51:58.415 --> 52:00.184
Of course I can. That's the good news.

52:00.184 --> 52:03.287
The bad news is that, unless
the grand jury surprises us,

52:03.287 --> 52:06.523
there will be a trial somewhere.

52:06.523 --> 52:09.560
So, ladies and gents,

52:09.560 --> 52:13.130
it's time to talk about that night.

52:13.130 --> 52:14.064
[door closes]

52:14.064 --> 52:16.333
Ah, perfect. Thank you, Luke.

52:17.968 --> 52:19.303
Thank you.

52:19.303 --> 52:21.238
Sit down. Take some notes.

52:25.743 --> 52:28.979
So, ahem, tell me what happened

52:28.979 --> 52:31.148
the night of Cole Lockhart's wedding.

52:31.148 --> 52:33.150
Look, I didn't kill Scott Lockhart.

52:33.150 --> 52:36.220
I am glad to hear that, Noah, but, sadly,

52:36.220 --> 52:39.256
the jury won't take my word for it, so...

52:42.126 --> 52:43.761
Uh... [exhales]

52:43.761 --> 52:45.095
it was a bad night.

52:45.095 --> 52:47.331
I didn't want to be there.

52:47.331 --> 52:49.299
It was her ex-husband, for fuck's sake,

52:49.299 --> 52:51.468
and, uh...

52:51.468 --> 52:53.537
I still don't know why
we were even invited.

52:53.537 --> 52:55.372
He was trying to be nice.

52:55.372 --> 52:57.274
- Was he?
- Yes.

53:01.111 --> 53:03.614
I was uncomfortable. I drank too much.

53:03.614 --> 53:05.382
We got into a fight.

53:05.382 --> 53:08.218
She left. I went to look for her.

53:08.218 --> 53:10.754
And I... I hit a deer.

53:10.754 --> 53:12.990
[Gottlief] You hit a deer?

53:14.258 --> 53:15.626
Yeah.

53:15.626 --> 53:18.062
Was Scott Lockhart

53:18.062 --> 53:20.097
riding the deer at the time?

53:20.097 --> 53:21.331
No.

53:21.331 --> 53:25.636
So they have you on
tape bribing a mechanic,

53:25.636 --> 53:28.739
telling the detective that
he did not fix your car

53:28.739 --> 53:30.240
the day after the wedding.

53:30.240 --> 53:32.376
I know it looks bad.

53:32.376 --> 53:34.344
Now I think I can get his testimony

53:34.344 --> 53:36.246
declared as inadmissible,
because I guarantee you,

53:36.246 --> 53:38.048
it was coerced,

53:38.048 --> 53:40.484
but that doesn't mean the jury
will forget it anytime soon,

53:40.484 --> 53:41.985
so please... [sucks in air]

53:41.985 --> 53:43.687
help me, Noah.

53:43.687 --> 53:45.322
Why the bribe?

53:48.992 --> 53:52.992
Did you know Scott Lockhart
was involved with my daughter?

53:53.097 --> 53:54.732
Yes, I'm aware of that.

53:54.732 --> 53:56.533
Well, so does everyone else.

53:56.533 --> 53:59.570
And, as you say, they don't
like me very much out there.

53:59.570 --> 54:03.273
My book wasn't exactly well received.

54:03.273 --> 54:05.609
People thought it was...

54:05.609 --> 54:08.245
exploitative.

54:08.245 --> 54:11.215
Look, I heard Scott got
